{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:34:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:34:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"844"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/844"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.4,0.16,0.05,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101495"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/844"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83934"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"3473"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43824"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101495"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents with complete dysphagia after trying to swallow a large lump of meat, which he felt got stuck. An endoscopy is performed, a food bolus disimpacted, and the following view of the oesophagus obtained (Image). On further questioning, the patient states that he has had difficulty in swallowing for several years and has had food stuck on a number of occasions.  Oesophageal biopsies are pending. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elimination diet","Esomeprazole","Budesonide","Methotrexate","Fluticasone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a typical history of a patient with eosinophilic oesophagitis and the endoscopy shows the characteristic concentric rings which occur secondary to eosinophil initiated oesophageal re-modelling and fibrosis. Eosinophilic oesophagitis (EoE) is defined as chronic immune-mediated eosinophil-predominant inflammation of the oesophageal mucosa. It mimics gastroesophageal reflux disease and may result in narrowing and stricture of the oesophagus. Typically, eosinophils are not found in the oeophagus, however it is an immunologically active organ and has the ability to recruit eosinophils in response to a variety of stimuli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitially an eight-week course of high dose proton pump inhibitor (PPI), such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eesomeprazole\u003C/strong\u003E, is suggested followed by repeat endoscopy and biopsy to distinguish between patients with PPI-responsive oesophageal eosinophilia from true eosinophilic oesophagitis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are two scenarios in which patients with esophageal eosinophilia improve with proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy. One group has typical gastroesophageal reflux disease (GORD) symptoms and findings like erosive oesophagitis or Barrett\u2019s oesophagus, with eosinophilia likely due to GORD and will typically improve with long term GORD therapy. The second group has symptoms and endoscopic features resembling eosinophilic esophagitis (EoE), but both symptoms and eosinophilia resolve with PPIs\u2014this is known as PPI-responsive esophageal eosinophilia (PPI-REE). It is unknown at present whether this latter group represents a GORD or EoE variant. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the diagnosis of true EoE is confirmed then the patient can be commenced on an \u003Cstrong\u003Eelimination diet, \u003C/strong\u003Etogether with topical corticosteroids  such as \u003Cstrong\u003Efluticasone\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Ebudesonide\u003C/strong\u003E. Patients should be counselled on swallowing rather than inhaling steroids. Patients without symptomatic or histological improvement after initial topical corticosteroids might benefit from a longer course, stronger steroid, systemic steroids, or oesophageal dilatation. The patient may also need referral to an allergist. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Food bolus obstruction and intermittent dysphagia in a younger patient should raise the possibility of eosinophilic oesophagitis.","Patients with eosinophils demonstrated on oesophageal biopsy should be commenced on a proton pump inhibitor, and endoscopic biopsies repeated after eight weeks to exclude PPI-responsive oesophageal eosinophilia."],"references":["Chen JW, Kao JY. Eosinophilic esophagitis: update on management and controversies. BMJ\u00a02017;359:j4482. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29133286/","Dellon ES, Lucend AJ, Schlag C, et al. Fluticasone Propionate Orally Disintegrating Tablet (APT-1011) for Eosinophilic Esophagitis: Randomized Controlled Q10 Trial Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol 2022, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cgh.2022.02.013 Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35181572/","Dellon ES, Gonsalves N, Hirano I, Furuta GT, Liacouras CA, Katzka DA; American College of Gastroenterology. ACG clinical guideline: Evidenced based approach to the diagnosis and management of esophageal eosinophilia and eosinophilic esophagitis (EoE). Am J Gastroenterol. 2013 May;108(5):679-92. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23567357/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83934"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14379"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14379"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/42e8f5d9-3f3b-4bb7-a8c7-8bef8bc4264b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/42e8f5d9-3f3b-4bb7-a8c7-8bef8bc4264b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":514,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83934"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T11:11:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T11:13:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"844"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101495"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data